{{About|the white separatist movement|the Germanic mysticist concept of Guido von List|Ariosophy|the worship of Wotan|Wotan (disambiguation)}} {{refimprove|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox religious group | group = Wotanism | flag = | population = | founder = [[David Lane (white supremacist)|David Lane]], Ron McVan, Katja Lane | regions = [[American Mountain States]], [[Europe]] | tablehdr = | region1 = | pop1 = | ref1 = | region2 = | pop2 = | ref2 = | region3 = | pop3 = | ref3 = | religions = [[Heathenry (new religious movement)|Heathenry]] ([[Nordic racial paganism]]) | scriptures = The "[[Fourteen Words]]", "[[88 Precepts]]", ''[[Hávamál]]'' <!--find a reliable source before adding any additional works --> | related-c = | notes = }} {{Neo-fascism}}
'''Wotansvolk''' is a form of [[White nationalism|white nationalist]], [[neo-völkisch]] paganism which was founded in the early 1990s by Ron McVan, Katja Lane and [[David Lane (white supremacist)|David Lane]] (1938–2007) while Lane was serving a 190-year prison sentence for his actions in connection with the white separatist revolutionary [[domestic terrorist]] organization [[The Order (white supremacist group)|The Order]], of which he was a member. After the founding of 14 Word Press by David Lane and his wife Katja to disseminate her husband's writings, Ron McVan joined the press in 1995 and founded Temple of Wotan (co-writing a book by that name). 14 Word Press - Wotansvolk proceeded to publish several books for the practice of Wotanism before becoming defunct in the early 2000s.
==History== Wotansvolk was launched after Lane published an article in 1995 titled "Wotan's Folk", which gave the group its name. ''Wotan'' is the Germanic name for [[Odin]], a central figure in [[Norse mythology]] and other [[Germanic mythology|Germanic mythologies]]. Lane had been publishing white supremacist and neopagan work under the name "14 Word Press" with his wife Katja Lane, and Ron McVan, an artist who had become involved with [[white separatism]] in the 1970s after reading the works of [[Ben Klassen]]. During this time, Wotansvolk published monthly pamphlets, maintained a [[website]], and made and sold Odinist religious objects. The publishers also operated a prison outreach program.<ref>{{harvnb|Gardell|2004|p=205–206}}</ref>
By 2001, prison groups in the [[United States|US]] were linked with Wotansvolk. Research by [[Mattias Gardell]] indicated "a pagan revival among the white prison population, including the conversion of whole [[prison gang]]s to the ancestral religion....Partly due to the reputation of Lane and its association with the legendary [[The Order (white supremacist group)|Brüders Schweigen]], Wotansvolk's name-recognition is high among the Aryan prison population".<ref name="Gardell217">{{harvnb|Gardell|2003|p=217}}</ref> Several members of The Order were practicing Wotanists, including its founder [[Robert Jay Mathews|Robert Mathews]], David Lane and Richard Scutari along with Richard Kemp.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2000/neo-pagans-peter-georgacarakos-david-lane-and-richard-scutari-publishing-prison|title=Neo-Pagans Peter Georgacarakos, David Lane and Richard Scutari Publishing from Prison|author=|date=|website=SPLCenter.org|access-date=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Wotansvolk is one of many groups active in prisoner outreach, but, according to Gardell, "Wotansvolk seem[ed] more successful in its outreach efforts than other Asatrú/Odinist programs".<ref name="Gardell217" /> Non-racist versions of Asatrú and Odinism are protected{{By whom|date=August 2017}} as free speech, but violent and racist religious materials, such as Wotanism, may be banned or restricted from prisons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mark Pitcavage of the Anti-Defamation League Discusses Race-Based Gangs and other Extremists in Prison|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2015/mark-pitcavage-anti-defamation-league-discusses-race-based-gangs-and-other-extremists|access-date=29 May 2017|work=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|date=Winter 2002|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Requires Prisons Give Special Consideration to Racist Pagans|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2009/supreme-court-requires-prisons-give-special-consideration-racist-pagans|access-date=29 May 2017|work=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|date=Fall 2009|language=en}}</ref>
==Beliefs== Wotansvolk practitioners see their [[religion]] as being rooted in ancestral European paganism which was driven underground, calling it the true spiritual heritage of the "Euro-Tribes".{{cn|date=May 2017}} Followers of the movement often selectively cite [[Carl Jung]]'s theories of an "Aryan [[collective subconscious]]" or [[race-soul]], specifically his 1936 essay "Wotan".<ref>{{harvnb|Gardell|2004|pp=208, 210–212}}</ref> The term Wotanism in modern times emphasizes [[white nationalism]], [[white separatism]] and an [[ethnocentric]], pan-European interpretation of [[modern Paganism]].
Unlike many [[Germanic neopaganism|Germanic neopagans]] within [[Heathenry (new religious movement)|Heathenry]], most Wotanists do not exclusively revere the [[Norse mythology|Norse]] pantheon of [[Asatru]] but rather all the deities of European mythology. Wotanists may reject [[Dualistic cosmology|dualism]], include [[Hermeticism|Hermetic]] ideas, and see David Lane as a [[prophet]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Lane's followers see the [[14 words]] and the [[88 Precepts]] as [[religious text|scripture]] and they primarily see the gods as [[Jungian archetypes]], although Lane said one could be a [[deist]], a [[pantheist]], or an [[atheist]] and still be Wotansvolk.<ref>see: Gambanreidi Statement; Wotanism by Professor Carl Gustav Jung Compiled by the late, Jost Turner [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/gambanreidi.geo/wotanjung.html&date=2009-10-25+22:28:02]</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Gardell|2003|p=270}}</ref> McVan and Lane have described many rituals and practices, none of which are required of practitioners.<ref>{{harvnb|Gardell|2004|pp=214–217}}</ref> Some Wotanists consider the ''[[Hávamál]]'' to be their holiest text while rites of practice are taken from Lane's writings.{{cn|date=May 2017}}
Lane often used 'Odinist' and 'Wotanist' as synonymous in his writings, and the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] regards Lane's Wotanism as a form of Odinism.<ref name="SPLC1998">{{cite news|title=New Brand of Racist Odinist Religion on the March|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/1998/new-brand-racist-odinist-religion-march|accessdate=30 May 2017|work=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|date=Winter 1998|language=en}}</ref> Lane stated that he had chosen the name "Wotanism" in conscious contrast to [[Anti-Racist Action|anti-racist]] heathens and those motivated by "universalist" ideology who Lane deemed were advancing [[White genocide conspiracy theory|white genocide]].{{cn|date=May 2017}}
Although Lane was contemptuous of [[Christianity]], viewing it as part of a Jewish conspiracy to rule the world, he viewed the [[Bible]] as containing secret codes hidden by pre-Christian, non-Jewish Aryan masters. Lane stated that this [[Bible code]] was carried over into the [[King James Version]], which he believed [[Sir Francis Bacon]] had translated. Lane also taught something which he called "Pyramid Prophecy" which according to him, said his name and birth-date were prophesied in the Bible as being connected to the coming of the [[Antichrist]], and embodying the spirits of [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], [[Thor]], and [[David|King David]] while being described as "the ''Man'' of prophecy", the "''666 Man''" and the "''Joseph Smith of Wotanism''".{{sfnp|Gardell|2003|p=381}}
Universalist Asatruars (notably [[The Troth]]) and some non-folkish [[Odinists]] have rejected what they perceive as an attempt to appropriate the revival of the ancient native faith of [[northern Europe]] for [[political]] and [[racial]] ends.<ref>{{harvnb|Gardell|2003|pp=273–283}}</ref> Folkish Odinists, such as [[Stephen McNallen]] of the [[Asatru Folk Assembly]], generally support Lane's version of Wotanism and the [[Fourteen Words]].<ref name="SPLC1998"/> Lane issued a declaration called "Moral Authority", as well, which calls the [[United States]] a "[[Flag of the United States|Red, White and Blue]] traveling mass murder machine" intent on committing [[White genocide conspiracy theory|genocide against white people]]. According to the declaration, "true moral authority belongs to those who resist" this purported genocide.<ref name="adl">{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/learn/ext_us/lane.asp?xpicked=2&item=lane |title=David Lane |website=[[Anti-Defamation League]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081103094309/http://www.adl.org/learn/ext_us/lane.asp?xpicked=2&item=lane |archivedate=November 3, 2008}}</ref>.<ref>{{harvnb|Gardell|2004|pp=202–204, 381}}</ref>
